blog.allometric.net/2008/01/nerds.html' title='No more moon missions'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=1153405706420005514' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/1153405706420005514/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/1153405706420005514'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/1153405706420005514'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-8548065503576948284</id><published>2007-12-07T07:11:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2008-09-03T14:34:23.722-07:00</updated><title type='text'>carapace</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp3.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/R9NcT3OPOsI/AAAAAAAAAC8/j5hRVH2xFkY/s1600-h/Farm1.JPG"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp3.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/R9NcT3OPOsI/AAAAAAAAAC8/j5hRVH2xFkY/s400/Farm1.JPG" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5175581893089770178" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We found brown dormant grasses tilting&lt;br /&gt;sideways along the shore, drift laid on&lt;br /&gt;spongy gravel we walked softly over.&lt;br /&gt;Low-angle sun scattering west to east&lt;br /&gt;lit forking tracks in mud the feeding geese had made.&lt;br /&gt;We walked silent miles in view of October mountains&lt;br /&gt;only to emerge upon this scene:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;An abandoned ice chest holding bait,&lt;br /&gt;and a blue plastic bag floating in water.&lt;br /&gt;Two folding chairs face the lake. Was a time&lt;br /&gt;this meant abduction, murder, intrigue...&lt;br /&gt;Knowing abandonment, we no longer concern ourselves&lt;br /&gt;with chairs unfilled with supervising adults, or children&lt;br /&gt;not pulling cold sodas from the chest.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A short time later, and reaching a point,&lt;br /&gt;the shore curves back and leaves us standing&lt;br /&gt;in the flat yellow rush of twilight&lt;br /&gt;streaming into the dark half of the sky.&lt;br /&gt;Guessing the bathymetry, casting in, then tipping back&lt;br /&gt;the second half of a bottle, legs crossed in wool pants,&lt;br /&gt;we reconstruct events from fragments.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Once startled by flashing trout in normally&lt;br /&gt;dead fetid canals, I took dusk wading&lt;br /&gt;expeditions after coming home from school&lt;br /&gt;in the wandering pickup. Reasoning,&lt;br /&gt;in bed, against warm parental breath laced with fetid mint&lt;br /&gt;persuaded me that right now I was scavenging strays&lt;br /&gt;washed down from upstream havens.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If we went to the same school, would we&lt;br /&gt;have set out like Lewis and Clark and together&lt;br /&gt;unearthed glinting chrysalides from beds upstream?&lt;br /&gt;Or been brought home scowling and stronger,&lt;br /&gt;convinced each was incomprehensible to the other.&lt;br /&gt;Not quite a choice, just the time in our lives when souls&lt;br /&gt;were condensing into metal plates.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We pause to catch and clean one rainbow&lt;br /&gt;and have no further luck with trout.&lt;br /&gt;Our limbs are lean, long and brittle now,&lt;br /&gt;draped in dusty, tattered plaid and we squat,&lt;br /&gt;with our long matted beards gathered between our legs.&lt;br /&gt;The red label bottle has one unwanted swig and we see&lt;br /&gt;something scuttle for our one caught fish.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We observe the movement in lantern light,&lt;br /&gt;watery shadows lurching hungrily&lt;br /&gt;among lake floor stones. Amused and peering&lt;br /&gt;out of gray sockets edged with joyful crowsfeet,&lt;br /&gt;we have ideas for those drawn to clean floating rainbows.&lt;br /&gt;Soon, faint twilight streams into our clicking bucket&lt;br /&gt;onto ruddy shells that shine like wet steel.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We'll eat what we catch, even the one&lt;br /&gt;caught trout we used as bait. On the lake&lt;br /&gt;the moon emerges through the surface,&lt;br /&gt;its weathered and pockmarked patina bulging&lt;br /&gt;like the ancient carapace of a grandfather crayfish&lt;br /&gt;without concern for the offspring we've scavenged in silence&lt;br /&gt;and are finally bringing home.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2007/12/carapace.html' title='carapace'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=8548065503576948284' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/8548065503576948284/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/8548065503576948284'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/8548065503576948284'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-1494906954293645231</id><published>2007-10-23T19:28:00.001-07:00</published><updated>2007-10-23T19:37:16.694-07:00</updated><title type='text'>laurel</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp0.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/Rx6uSRSrcuI/AAAAAAAAACg/IK7pHPi1TZs/s1600-h/Lo_eyes2.jpeg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp0.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/Rx6uSRSrcuI/AAAAAAAAACg/IK7pHPi1TZs/s400/L