. after the speech I caught the 9:15 bus home. I will probably never have to serve in the military and when the war started my retreating hairline was barely noticeable. tonight, looking at my reflection in greasy bus windows, there is no denying that I am going bald.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2007/01/hair-club-for-men.html' title='hair club for men'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=381625573255824284' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/381625573255824284/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/381625573255824284'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/381625573255824284'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-8797497194583329253</id><published>2006-12-19T23:03:00.001-08:00</published><updated>2008-03-10T15:08:19.118-07:00</updated><title type='text'>not eating him</title><content type='html'>once, in another country, i ate a dog. i didn't mean to order it, but the menu was in a different language and I accidentally pointed to a dish of noodles stirfried with pieces of a dog. i ate the pieces of meat not knowing that it was a dog until i saw the golden brown roast dog laying on a cutting board in the middle of the restaurant. the dog had gleaming white teeth and pieces of meat carved from its sides. i looked down at the meat on my plate and thought about my own dog laying on the couch in front of the tv. i ate some of the noodles with a dog. but i would never eat my dog. i love my dog and i would never eat him. the roast dog that i ate tasted okay, but i will never eat a dog again. sometimes when i am watching tv and my dog is sitting next to me on the couch i say to myself that i will never eat him. i tell him. when i am cooking a vegetarian dish in the kitchen and he sits by my feet and begs, i am not thinking about cooking him. he just sits there next to the oven watches me cook, and  i am not thinking about putting him in the oven. i will always love the dog and never eat him. i am not in another country where it might be socially acceptable to eat my dog. when i am watching tv with my dog and that commercial featuring that one dog comes on i try to get my dog to watch and see the other dog and recognize that it is a dog, but  he just looks at me and puts his head back down on the couch and closes his eyes. but i recognize the dog. that other dog on tv. not my dog.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/12/not-eat-him.html' title='not eating him'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=8797497194583329253' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/8797497194583329253/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/8797497194583329253'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/8797497194583329253'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-2720109960567768219</id><published>2006-12-18T16:05:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2006-12-31T17:52:13.769-08:00</updated><title type='text'>dusty springfield</title><content type='html'>She was a pink prize-fighter&lt;br /&gt;who wore off her skin&lt;br /&gt;where the thumb flicks the lighter.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Gentle morning waves rolled in,&lt;br /&gt;woke me up too soon.&lt;br /&gt;She said water made it happen.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I made the same mistakes too.&lt;br /&gt;Put candles on cupcakes,&lt;br /&gt;now I'm chewing on an abscessed tooth.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/12/cupcake.html' title='dusty springfield'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=2720109960567768219' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/2720109960567768219/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/2720109960567768219'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/2720109960567768219'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-1574295179199703372</id><published>2006-12-16T12:30:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2006-12-19T07:26:11.878-08:00</updated><title type='text'>Spitting blood (while revisiting Hanoi)</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp1.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RYY5uUFUU3I/AAAAAAAAAAY/RuDWqiBr7wI/s1600-h/viet36.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp1.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RYY5uUFUU3I/AAAAAAAAAAY/RuDWqiBr7wI/s400/viet36.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5009755103324033906" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;1am&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;On the third cup the cafe sua da starts to act like an amphetamine. My hindbrain is resonating and I can see hot bones glowing under the golden-brown skin of the two mongrels on the chopping block. Their lips have curled away from their ivory teeth into an ironic grin. Please God don't let this be their savory flesh between my teeth. It's definitely not beef.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;2am&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"Stop whining, you'll never get your change back. Free market or no, this is still a communist country. Gimme that bag." The betel nuts are wrapped in fresh tobacco with a smear of white lime inside. "Chew it a little and cram the pulp between your gum and lips." She tells me it feels like her belly is filling up with warm sloshing blood and that it's good, calming. We spit crimson streams in unison.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;3am&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This guy that looks like a Vietnamese David Bowie grins at us and slaps his forearm with his fingers. The glittery polish on his nails sparkles with the light form the sodium lamps above us on the overpass . Its a question. I look over and smile "Do we want that?" Keiko shakes her half-Japanese head, makes a frowny face. We just sit there on the curb, kicking the dust around a little while David Bowie and his friend examine us. Eventually, the man comes back on his Honda Dream and says he can't find any. We turn David Bowie down again and then leave. The olive drab driver that was sleeping in his cyclo when we passed a half hour ago whistles at us as we pass. He looks like he was in the war and he can conjure smoke from the seat of his ancient cyclo. There is a handoff behind the garbage truck.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;4am&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"My take on it is this...passion is consuming, like a flame. It burns until there is nothing left to burn, and then youre both left standing there cold and bewildered, wondering how to get warm again."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"Maybe thats true" I say, "but what about just wanting company?" We kick our legs around in the muggy air between the windowsill and the street, quiet for a while. "This shit tastes like the newspaper it came in"&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"Yeah, lets smoke the rest."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The last two shirtless men are talking in soft, sleepy voices down on the street as their tired daughters stack the plastic stools together and carry them inside. This morning it will be re-election day,  and  we are watching a worker slowly make his way down the street putting flags up on the power poles.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/12/spitting-blood-while-revisiting-hanoi.html' title='Spitting blood (while revisiting Hanoi)'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=1574295179199703372' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/1574295179199703372/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/1574295179199703372'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/1574295179199703372'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-7760902589523788245</id><published>2006-12-16T00:21:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2006-12-16T12:29:21.603-08:00</updated><title type='text'>shaping</title><content type='html'>Tonight, I was walking home from a bar,&lt;br /&gt;and thinking too much.&lt;br /&gt;It was snowing.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I stopped outside the bakery window&lt;br /&gt;and watched James shape loaves&lt;br /&gt;for a little while.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Inside, ESPN sports guys talking,&lt;br /&gt;James rolls out french baguettes.&lt;br /&gt;Batards relaxing.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Rye boules rising in wicker bannetons,&lt;br /&gt;yeast wafting through the air.&lt;br /&gt;My house, a cold mile&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Under the streetlamps the blue snow looking&lt;br /&gt;golden. Tomorrow&lt;br /&gt;I'll wake up and think&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"I will go buy a fresh loaf," but Gina&lt;br /&gt;gives it to me for free&lt;br /&gt;just because I smiled.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/12/tomorrow.html' title='shaping'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=7760902589523788245' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/7760902589523788245/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/7760902589523788245'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/7760902589523788245'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-8576190086944349894</id><published>2006-12-07T19:27:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2006-12-07T20:23:05.407-08:00</updated><title type='text'>the desert</title><content type='html'>It was a big piece of undeveloped land across the creek behind our house. There were cottonwoods by the pond, clumps of scrub oak in the dry areas, and then big piles of rock and construction debris in between. During flood season huge bulldozers and shovels would come down and push the granite river rocks around and dredge all the mud out of the rapidly filling up pond. Still, half our yard got washed away one year. You could see the tracks that those big machines left in the ground for years afterward. That was where the Nunnelly boys hid the first Playboy I ever saw. Kirk and Clayton took me down there to look at it one afternoon -  it was hidden in a clump of oaks across the creek where you couldn't see any houses. Same place we would go to turn over rocks and find scorpions and shoot at magpies with the bow and arrow. It was the best place for porno, scorpions, and shooting things that we had in our neigborhood. One winter there was a family of coyotes that lived over there for a few weeks. I would wake up early and watch them skulking around across the creek at dawn, and I could hear them howling from my bed. Sometimes I would imagine the coyotes walking through my yard in the middle of the night, just on the other side of the wall a few feet from where I was trying to sleep. We used to walk up along the creek to a place called Big Rock. It was in the hollow below Alta high school and we thought there would be hippies drinking beer and smoking cigarettes up there. One winter we even went up there and walked right on the frozen creek. It was sunny and you could skate across the icy parts to the rocky parts, and then push off and slide to the next rocky part. In some places the ice was brittle and crumbly and would shatter into sugary powder when you hit it. Clay dunked his foot in the water underneath, but we kept going to Big Rock. There were never any hippies there. Just a big rock covered with grafitti and the dirt was worn all fine and dusty like lots of people had been walking around there before us, looking for things to do.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp2.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RXjoGAD4zzI/AAAAAAAAAAM/Rcqd7fXd2D4/s1600-h/deercreek_0107.JPG"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp2.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RXjoGAD4zzI/AAAAAAAAAAM/Rcqd7fXd2D4/s400/deercreek_0107.JPG" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5006006175615471410" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/12/desert.html' title='the desert'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=8576190086944349894' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/8576190086944349894/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/8576190086944349894'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/8576190086944349894'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-116469809617790013</id><published>2006-11-27T22:56:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2006-11-30T12:29:18.643-08:00</updated><title type='text'>Voice-over</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/x/blogger/4587/2729/1600/995636/burma06.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/x/blogger/4587/2729/400/814139/burma06.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Nobody's perfect.&lt;br /&gt;There was never a perfect person around.&lt;br /&gt;You just got half devil and half angel in you&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;She promised herself she'd lead a good life from now on.&lt;br /&gt;She blamed it all on herself.&lt;br /&gt;She didnt care if she was happy or not,&lt;br /&gt;she just wanted to make up for what she did wrong.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The sun looks ghostly when there's a mist on the river&lt;br /&gt;and everything's quiet. I never knowed it before.&lt;br /&gt;An' you could see people on the shore,&lt;br /&gt;but it was far off and you couldn't see what they were doin.&lt;br /&gt;They were probly callin for help or somethin,&lt;br /&gt;or they were tryin to bury somebody or somethin.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We seen trees that the leaves are shakin and it looks like&lt;br /&gt;shadows of guys comin at you an' stuff.&lt;br /&gt;We heard owls sqwawking away, hootin' away.&lt;br /&gt;We didn't know where we were goin, what we were gonna do.&lt;br /&gt;I've never been on a boat before&lt;br /&gt;that was the first time.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Some sights that I saw was really spooky&lt;br /&gt;that it gave me goosebumps. I felt like&lt;br /&gt;cold hands touchin the back of my neck and,&lt;br /&gt;and it could be the dead coming for me or something.&lt;br /&gt;I remember this guy his name was Blackjack, he died.&lt;br /&gt;He only had one leg and he died,&lt;br /&gt;and I think that was Blackjack&lt;br /&gt;makin those noises.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style=";font-family:times new roman;font-size:85%;"  &gt;Linda, from Terence Malick's &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Days of Heaven&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/11/voice-over.html' title='Voice-over'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=116469809617790013' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/116469809617790013/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116469809617790013'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116469809617790013'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-116336269606969488</id><published>2006-11-12T12:08:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2006-11-29T17:24:30.080-08:00</updated><title type='text'>back to the lake</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/x/blogger/4587/2729/1600/863864/bookcliffs.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/x/blogger/4587/2729/400/490033/bookcliffs.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;we were fixing a flat in green river when he went down&lt;br /&gt;we heard the crash of diving flukes&lt;br /&gt;felt the stillness grow&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;we went out around the town smashing old clawfoot bathtubs&lt;br /&gt;stealing some things and walked into&lt;br /&gt;a secret pigeon roost&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;it was one floor above state liquors, all along the walls&lt;br /&gt;were rows of movie seats in storage&lt;br /&gt;painted white as snow&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;our footsteps crackled and every sentence mingled strangely&lt;br /&gt;with flapping sounds, it didn't matter&lt;br /&gt;which words we used&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;across the street all the cues were crooked but they dont charge&lt;br /&gt;for the game if you keep buying drinks&lt;br /&gt;we amused some locals&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;they took us to their old trailer on the outskirts of town&lt;br /&gt;and we waited for something new to come&lt;br /&gt;from the bottle or the bonfire&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;we'll never remember their names, woke up in storm thick air&lt;br /&gt;with raindrops pattering softly&lt;br /&gt;sizzling on last nights coals&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;we put on our shoes, shook the dust out of our clothes and hair&lt;br /&gt;and wound our way through the greasewood&lt;br /&gt;to ned's house of tires&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;*      *      *&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;driving along the base of the book cliffs if felt like we were floating outside of the car, just hangin' up there in space tethered to the bumper. we looked around and tried to find old miners' cabins in the cliffs, abandoned corrals, buzzards picking at old carcasses, or pronghorns out racing each other all over those bone dry plains between woodside and price. we never really saw much that we could tell what it was, and we mostly were just trying to keep our minds busy. just flappin' around up there, never gettin' caught on the girders below an overpass or anything, all the way back to the lake.&lt;/div&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/11/back-to-lake.html' title='back to the lake'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=116336269606969488' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/116336269606969488/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116336269606969488'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116336269606969488'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-116329348850371311</id><published>2006-11-11T16:59:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2006-11-12T10:02:46.426-08:00</updated><title type='text'></title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/aung_san_suu_kyi_portrait.gif"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/400/aung_san_suu_kyi_portrait.png" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:book antiqua;"&gt;&lt;i&gt;"Within a system which denies the existence of                 basic human rights, fear tends to be the order of                 the day...A most insidious form of fear is that                 which masquerades as common sense or even wisdom,                 condemning as foolish, reckless, insignficant, or                 futile the small, daily acts of courage which                 help to preserve man's self-respect and inherent                 human dignity."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;-Aung San Suu Kyi&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/span&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/11/within-system-which-denies-existence.html' title=''/><link rel='related' href='http://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/12/world/asia/12cnd-myanmar.html?hp&amp;ex=1163394000&amp;en=23eb3efefc622c4c&amp;ei=5094&amp;partner=homepage' title=''/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=116329348850371311' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/116329348850371311/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116329348850371311'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116329348850371311'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-116263244060543098</id><published>2006-11-04T01:06:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2006-11-04T11:37:16.523-08:00</updated><title type='text'>perch</title><content type='html'>My new computer dominates.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;* * * * * * * * * * * *&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;i built a new computer&lt;br /&gt;that was much more powerful than I expected&lt;br /&gt;so i began to fear it&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;it sat under my desk droning seductively&lt;br /&gt;but i couldnt think&lt;br /&gt;of ways to put its sleek silicon to work&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;i was intimidated&lt;br /&gt;by the number of calculations it needed to do&lt;br /&gt;to be used to its potential&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;all i really wanted to do was to check my email&lt;br /&gt;create some text files&lt;br /&gt;and a spreadsheet with names and numbers of all my friends&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;i released it into the jordan river&lt;br /&gt;and watched it float downstream to find its special purpose&lt;br /&gt;and reach for the brass ring&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;twelve years later i was out spearfishing for marsh suckers&lt;br /&gt;my beard had grown long&lt;br /&gt;the october brine flies were buzzing in waves&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;i saw an angular shape rising&lt;br /&gt;over the grey mud flats and low clumps of iodinebush&lt;br /&gt;it was my powerful computer&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;i went to see what it had been up to all these years&lt;br /&gt;it looked older&lt;br /&gt;tiny patterns in pink salt crystals covered the base&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;and the top edge of the case&lt;br /&gt;was worn into a rough curve and painted white from years&lt;br /&gt;of being used as a perch&lt;/div&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/11/perch.html' title='perch'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=116263244060543098' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/116263244060543098/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116263244060543098'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116263244060543098'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-116263073555654163</id><published>2006-11-04T00:37:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2006-11-12T11:42:30.613-08:00</updated><title type='text'>Bonneville</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/IMG_0192.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/400/IMG_0192.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You think you are under pressure now?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Back in the Pleistocene, the space you now occupy was under 1000 feet of fresh water. The valleys we live in, from here to southern Idaho, bulging west beyond Wendover, NV, and south past tiny Milford, UT, were all lake floors. There were thousands of feet of water pushing down on every living thing in this place.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Imagine living under that kind of pressure. Thankfully, about 15,000 years ago the dam holding back all this water broke and Lake Bonneville flooded north into Idaho.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Today, with the heaviness lifted, the former lake floors we walk, run, and jump on are free of all that pressure and are reacting appropriately. The earth's crust is rising, slowly, in a process called isostatic rebound. Its been going on ever since the dam broke and the rate of rebound is now slowing down.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Every time your feet leave the ground you travel an airborn arc over the earth and reach an apex that defines the greatest distance you will be from the earth. At this apex you unconciously predict where the ground will be when you land. Your brain calculates a location below where mother earth is waiting and your muscles prepare for the impact to come at a particular time.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Around here, the deceleration of isostatic rebound means that your calculation is always a little off. Because the earth is rising to meet you more slowly than it was when you jumped off of it, you will remain airborn for a fraction of a second longer than you calculated at your apex, causing your heart to drop into your guts for a disconcerting moment. Then the earth will solidly strike your feet just barely after you expect it to, imparting a subtle sense of the unreal to the rest of your life.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.allometric.net/2006/11/bonneville.html' title='Bonneville'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=30719777&amp;postID=116263073555654163' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.allometric.net/feeds/116263073555654163/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116263073555654163'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/30719777/posts/default/116263073555654163'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-30719777.post-115690292331374934</id><published>2006-08-29T18:52:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-08-29T19:32:24.636-07:00</updated><title type='text'>I've been rather busy lately</title><content type='html'>building a new computer. the GRIZ-9000 will be up and running soon. it will dominate your shit. my shit. all the earth's shit will be dominated by my new computer.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0696.0.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center